{With 14 points you will naturally open the bidding. You should open a 4-card \D suit rather than a 3-card \C suit. Partner responds 1\H.  

Partner might have bid a 4-card suit so you cannot support \Hs with only 3. Instead, you describe your balanced, minimum opener by bidding 1NT. Partner then bids 3NT and you pass.

North plays 3NT. East leads the \CK.

<b>North plays 3NT. East leads the \CK.</b>

Winners: \S 3 : \H 2 : \D 1 : \C 1 : Total = 7

You need to find 2 more winners and they can come from the \D suit. You can finesse East for the \DK. If he has it then you will get 3 extra tricks, but even if West has the \DK you can still make 2 winners.

The problem is that if you win the first or second \C and then try the \D finesse West may win and still have a \C to lead back to his partner. So you should hold up the \CA until the third round of the suit. Then if West wins the \DK he may not have another \C.

Imagine that you had won either the first or second \C. When West won the \DK he would still have had a \C to return to East's hand. You would have lost 4 \C tricks and the \DK.

But what if West <b>DID</b> have another \C when he won the \DK?

Suppose you held up until the third \C. When West won the \DK  here he had a fourth \C to return to East's hand. That means the \C suit split 4-4 so you would have lost only 3 \C tricks and the \DK.}
[Play "W"]CK

